==English==
===Etymology===
From Egyptian ''wšbty'' ‘answerer’, replacing ''šwbty'', perhaps from ''šwɜb'' ‘persea wood’, perhaps the original material.

===Pronunciation===
[[IPA]]: /u:'ʃæbti/

===Noun===
{{en-noun2|'''ushabti'''|'''[[ushabtiu]]''' or '''[[ushabtis]]'''}}
# in ancient Egypt, a figurine of a dead person, placed in their tomb to do their work for them in the afterlife
#:*'''1886''': These little images were called in Egyptian “'''Ushabti''',” or “Respondents,” and were in fact supposed to act as servants of the deceased, it being their duty to answer for him and serve as his substitutes when called upon to do labourer's work — ''The Times'', 1 Sep 1886, p.13 col. A